rows.text: Played to celebrate the coronation of George IV
Players had only nine men, but the match was still considered first-class.
Gentlemen defended a smaller-than-normal wicket of 22 by 6 inches.
Players defended a larger-than-normal wicket of four stumps measuring 36 by 12 inches.
Gentlemen broke a winless streak of 20 matches (19 losses, 1 drawn).
Players broke a winless streak of 19 matches (16 losses, 3 drawn).
Gentlemen added 46 for the last wicket to win.
Gentlemen, chasing 113 to win, went from 56/0 to 111 all out in second innings.
Gentlemen, set 150 to win, were bowled out for 149.
Digby Jephson (Gentlemen) took 6–21 with underarm lobs.
The umpires were replaced at lunch on the first day after an objection from Gentlemen captain W. G. Grace.
Tip Foster (102 & 136) was the first man to score a century in each innings in these matches.
Gentlemen made 500/2 declared following on (C. B. Fry 232*).
Jack Hobbs, uniquely, scored hundreds in all the three matches in 1919.

Players captain Jack Hobbs scored 266, a record in Gentlemen v Players matches.
